---
import TTELayout from '~/layouts/TTELayout.astro';
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import carlPortrait from '~/assets/images/IMG_1167.jpeg';

const breadcrumbLd = JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://www.toptier-electrical.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'About', item: 'https://www.toptier-electrical.com/about' },
  ],
});
---

<TTELayout
  title="About | Owner-Operated Master Electrician in West MI"
  description="Meet the licensed master electrician behind Top Tier Electrical. Learn our process, workmanship standards, and service approach across West Michigan."
  ogImage="https://www.toptier-electrical.com/images/og/pages/about.png"
  jsonLd={[breadcrumbLd]}
>
  <main id="main-content">
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <ol>
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
        <li aria-current="page">About</li>
      </ol>
    </nav>
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-content">
        <h1>Owner-Operated Electrical Contracting Built for Long-Term Reliability</h1>
        <p>
          I started Top Tier Electrical to deliver clear communication, clean code-correct work, and planning that helps
          clients avoid expensive rework later.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="container meet-section">
      <div class="meet-grid">
        <figure class="meet-photo">
          <Picture
            src={carlPortrait}
            alt="Carl, Master Electrician and owner of Top Tier Electrical, at his home office desk in Allegan, MI, surrounded by NFPA 70 National Electrical Code books and electrical training materials."
            widths={[360, 480, 720, 960]}
            sizes="(min-width: 768px) 480px, calc(100vw - 2rem)"
            formats={['avif', 'webp']}
            fallbackFormat="jpeg"
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
          />
        </figure>
        <div class="meet-body">
          <h2>Meet Carl</h2>
          <p>
            Carl is the master electrician and owner behind Top Tier Electrical. His desk stack tells the work story:
            NFPA 70 National Electrical Code, 2023 edition right next to the 2020 — plus applied grounding and bonding,
            commercial and industrial wiring, instrumentation and process control, and the custom training binders from
            his master's certification work. The reference shelf isn't decoration; it's how he keeps every job
            code-correct on the current edition.
          </p>
          <p>
            Owner-operated means when you call, you reach the person doing the work — not a dispatcher or sub. Carl
            pulls permits in his own name and signs every walkthrough.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Off the clock, family comes first.</strong> Kids running through the office, the dog as the only foreman.
            Outside West Michigan jobsites you'll find him in the woods or on the water — hunting season is sacred and the
            camo on the wall isn't decoration.
          </p>
          <p>
            Top Tier Electrical was built to be the contractor Carl would want his own family to call. <a
              href="https://aca-prod.accela.com/lara/"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              target="_blank">Verify MI License #6220430 on the LARA portal</a
            >.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="container card proof-section">
      <h2>Two True Stories About Doing Right by the Customer</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        I don't expect you to take my word that I'll tell you the truth, even when the truth costs me the bigger job.
        Here are two real situations — one residential, one commercial — where the right call was the smaller one for
        me. They're the clearest way I know to show how I think.
      </p>

      <article class="proof-story">
        <h3>I talked them into something that wasn't even electrical.</h3>
        <p>
          A Grand Rapids flip. The GC brought me in to wire part of the home, and I walked it with him. I already knew
          the owners separately.
        </p>
        <p>
          End of the walk I was staring down the alleyway kitchen. On the other side of the wall — a raised platform off
          the garage. No direct access from the kitchen; the only way over was up a set of stairs. Dead space. What any
          growing family would actually want is more pantry, right there, off the kitchen. I was insistent. Nothing in
          it for me. I told the GC. Then I went to the owners and said what I'd do.
        </p>
        <p>
          They built it. The home's still on the market, and I know the renovation more than doubled what they spent.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm not telling you that to brag about ROI. I'm telling you because that's the whole job to me: pay attention,
          and tell the truth about what actually works. The wiring was the easy part.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="proof-story">
        <h3>A manufacturer was about to spend $100K on the wrong upgrade. I told them to stop.</h3>
        <p>
          A large multi-site manufacturer — operations out of state plus an existing facility here on Consumers Energy —
          called me in on a plan to upgrade their service from 400 amps to 2,000 amps. Roughly $100,000. Easy money to
          take.
        </p>
        <p>
          The first thing I checked wasn't what they wanted to buy. It was what the utility could physically deliver,
          and what the building actually needed. Consumers could supply 1,600 amps there — so a 2,000-amp design was a
          check they couldn't cash. I went deeper: walked their real equipment, ran the actual loads, and mapped roughly
          <strong>20 more pieces of equipment</strong> they expected to add over the next several years.
        </p>
        <p>
          The honest answer wasn't "buy a bigger panel." They were outgrowing secondary service altogether. The right
          call was <strong>primary power</strong> and owning their own transformer — a harder conversation, longer timeline,
          capital project. The right move for the next 10–20 years.
        </p>
        <p>
          I could have built exactly what they asked for. Another contractor probably will, if they hand the same spec
          out again — quote it, take the check, leave them with a service that still doesn't do what they actually need.
          They asked me for a proposal. The honest one was the one I gave them.
        </p>
        <p>They haven't broken ground. They're researching primary right now.</p>
      </article>

      <p class="proof-footer">
        That's the standard. If you want an electrician who proposes what you actually need — not just what you asked
        for — let's talk.
      </p>
      <style>
        .proof-section .lead {
          font-size: 1.05em;
          line-height: 1.55;
          margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        .proof-story {
          margin: 28px 0;
          padding: 20px 22px;
          border-left: 4px solid #d4a017;
          background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.025);
          border-radius: 6px;
        }
        .proof-story h3 {
          margin-top: 0;
          font-size: 1.18em;
          line-height: 1.35;
        }
        .proof-story p {
          margin: 10px 0;
          line-height: 1.55;
        }
        .proof-footer {
          font-style: italic;
          margin-top: 24px;
        }
      </style>
    </section>
    <section class="container card">
      <h2>The Top Tier Standard: Why Precision is Non-Negotiable</h2>
      <p>In the electrical trade, there is a dangerous gap between "functional" and "correct."</p>
      <p>
        I’ve spent years entering homes and businesses in West Michigan only to find that the "emergency" I was called
        for was actually set in motion months or years prior. It’s usually the result of a rushed installation, a
        misunderstood code, or a contractor who prioritized speed over safety. I founded Top Tier Electrical to close
        that gap.
      </p>
      <h3>My Philosophy: Workmanship That Lives Behind Your Walls</h3>
      <p>
        I believe that the most important part of my work is the part you’ll never see. While a light turning on is the
        goal, the integrity of the circuit and the safety of the load are what actually matter. When you hire me, you
        aren't just paying for a repair; you are investing in:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Engineering over Improvisation:</strong> Every project—from a simple outlet move to a full commercial service
          upgrade—is approached with a "measure twice, cut once" mentality.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Radical Reliability:</strong> "Contractor ghosting" is an epidemic. I’ve built my reputation on clear communication,
          arriving when I say I will, and providing a scope of work that is as transparent as it is thorough.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Future-Proofing:</strong> I don’t just fix the problem you have today; I look at your system’s capacity
          for tomorrow. Whether it's EV charging or smart home integration, I ensure your investment scales with your life.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h3>The Top Tier Four-Pillar Process</h3>
      <p>To ensure 100% client confidence, I follow a strict protocol on every job site:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Forensic Diagnosis:</strong> We find the root cause, not just the symptom.</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Expert Consultation:</strong> I explain your options in plain English, empowering you to make the right
          decision for your budget and safety.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Clean Execution:</strong> My workspaces are tidy, my code is clean, and my respect for your property is
          paramount.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Verification:</strong> Every job includes a final walkthrough to ensure the results exceed the standards
          you expect.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Rooted in West Michigan</h3>
      <p>
        Based in Holland and serving the greater Grand Rapids and Zeeland areas, I am an owner-operator. When you call,
        you talk to the person doing the work. My license number—MI #6220430—is more than a registration; it is my
        personal guarantee that your project will be code-correct, safe, and built to last.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Let’s Get It Done Right the First Time.</strong></p>
      <p>If you’re tired of the "quick fix" and ready for a professional standard, I’m ready to help.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="container trust-section">
      <h2>What to Expect</h2>
      <div class="trust-grid">
        <article class="trust-item">
          <h3>Diagnose</h3>
          <p>We identify the root issue and gather the details that affect scope.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="trust-item">
          <h3>Explain</h3>
          <p>You get options explained clearly, including future-proof recommendations.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="trust-item">
          <h3>Scope</h3>
          <p>Clear scope before work begins, with permits and inspections discussed upfront.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="trust-item">
          <h3>Execute &amp; Verify</h3>
          <p>Clean, code-correct installation with walkthrough before closeout.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="container gallery-section">
      <h2>Real Work, Real Standards</h2>
      <p>See panels, EV chargers, lighting upgrades, and commercial service work completed across West Michigan.</p>
      <p><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/gallery">View Project Gallery</a></p>
    </section>
    <section class="cta-section">
      <h2>Ready to Work Together?</h2>
      <p>
        Call <a href="tel:+16163347159" data-ga-event="phone_click" data-ga-label="about__phone">(616) 334-7159</a> or email
        <a href="mailto:info@toptier-electrical.com">info@toptier-electrical.com</a> to confirm scope and scheduling.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/booking"
        class="btn btn-primary"
        data-ga-event="clear_estimate_click"
        data-ga-label="Get a Clear Estimate"
        data-ga-destination="/booking">Get a Clear Estimate</a
      >
    </section>
  </main>
</TTELayout>
